The commission's recommendation for federal standards on birth certificates and IDs, including driver's licenses, has sparked concerns in several states.
Senator Lamar Alexander criticized the new rules, labeling them as costly and burdensome.
Some states are considering legal challenges or outright disobedience.
Immigrant rights groups oppose the REAL ID Act, arguing it won't enhance security.
The Act mandates stricter verification for driver's licenses, targeting undocumented immigrants.
The push for a national ID system faces resistance, with civil libertarians warning of privacy risks.
Congress aims to tighten ID requirements, potentially impacting access to benefits and travel.
